      <h1 class=3D"entry-title">True Shooting Percentage (TS%)</h1>
   =20
  </header>     =20


<div class=3D"entry-content content">


  <hr class=3D"x-hr">
<nav aria-label=3D"breadcrumbs" class=3D"rank-math-breadcrumb"><p><a href=
=3D"https://www.nbastuffer.com/">Home</a><span class=3D"separator"> =C2=BB =
</span><a href=3D"https://www.nbastuffer.com/analytics101/">Analytics 101</=
a><span class=3D"separator"> =C2=BB </span><span class=3D"last">True Shooti=
ng Percentage (TS%)</span></p></nav>
<b>True shooting percentage</b>, aka TS%, is a metric that factors&nbsp;a p=
layer=E2=80=99s or a team=E2=80=99s performance at the free-throw line and =
considers the efficiency of all types of shots. This <a href=3D"https://www=
.nbastuffer.com/nba-stats/">NBA statistic</a> helps us compare players with=
 varying responsibilities and shooting abilites on the floor. A higher True=
 Shooting Percentage generally indicates a more efficient scorer, while a l=
ower percentage indicates a less efficient scorer, while other aspects such=
 as shot selection and offensive role should also be taken into account whe=
n evaluating a player=E2=80=99s overall performance.<p></p>
<p>True Shooting Percentage (TS%) could be the clearest and easily measured=
 metric that boils all three methods of scoring into one number. </p>
<div id=3D"" class=3D"x-alert x-alert-info x-alert-block" style=3D""><h6 cl=
ass=3D"h-alert">True Shooting Percentage Formula</h6>
<br>
TS%=3D0.5*(Total&nbsp;Points)/{(Total Field Goal Attempts) + 0.44*(Total Fr=
ee Throw Attempts)}<br>
<br>
<img fetchpriority=3D"high" decoding=3D"async" class=3D"x-img x-img-rounded=
" style=3D"max-width: 50%;" src=3D"https://cdn.nbastuffer.com/wp-content/up=
loads/2025/02/ts.png" alt=3D"True Shooting Percentage Formula">
</div>
<p>Note that just like in all other tempo-free (adjusted for team pace and =
minutes played) NBA stats, the =E2=80=9C0.44=E2=80=9D multiplier estimates =
all free throws which take up possessions. As you know, technical free thro=
ws and =E2=80=98and 1=E2=80=99s do not take up possessions. If one player c=
hecks in the court and drills a 3P shot and doesn=E2=80=99t play for the re=
st of the game, then his TS% would reach a maximum, 150%.</p>
<p>Let=E2=80=99s look at <a href=3D"https://www.nbastuffer.com/nba-stats/pl=
ayer/">some real-life examples</a> to better understand TS%, True Shooting =
Percentage:</p>
<ul>
<li>Stephen Curry: Throughout his career, Curry, widely recognized as one o=
f the greatest shooters in NBA history, has consistently had high True Shoo=
ting Percentages. He is well-known for his three-point shooting prowess and=
 ability to draw fouls. Curry had a True Shooting Percentage of 65.3% in th=
e 2020-2021 season. This shows that he scored efficiently when all of his f=
ield goals, three-pointers, and free throws are considered.</li>
<li>Alperen Sengun: The Rockets=E2=80=99 powerful big talen primarily score=
s on close-range jumpers and dunks. He also attempts three-point shots and =
is  an average free-throw shooter. His True Shooting Percentage, on the oth=
er hand, stays high due to his strong field goal percentage and above the l=
eague average free-throw attempts. Sengun has been posting a True Shooting =
Percentage of 54% in the 2024-2025 season, demonstrating his all-around ski=
lls all over the court.</li>
</ul>
<p class=3D"wpg-back-link"><a href=3D"https://www.nbastuffer.com/analytics-=
101/">Back to Analytics101</a></p><p> =20

</p></div>

